	<table cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#000000" width="470">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<table cellpadding="10" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" width="468">
					<tr>
						<td>
							<b>Workshops</b><br />
							E3 workshops offer a unique opportunity to learn 
what it takes to succeed in today's competitive 
computer game industry. Expose yourself to some 
of the industry's most talented - and 
experienced - professionals as they discuss 
elements of design, market research, and 
promotion. Learn from experts and apply that 
knowledge to your own game development or 
publishing enterprise
</td>
					</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</table>

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="4"></a>W1 - Read the Marketplace for Added Profit</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:30 AM<br />
		Room: 411<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		How does a consumer end up buying a game? What 
are the steps or stages s/he goes through in 
making a purchase? Learn how the industry makes 
wise use of market research, in-game player 
metrics, focus groups, and fourth-party 
developers to create and support a top-selling 
title. Come away from this session with an 
understanding of the modern tools behind the 
blockbuster hits, the role that pre-release 
research can play in influencing development 
ideas, and how you can tap some of those 
techniques for your own.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="5"></a>W2 - The Design Document: Necessary, Necessary Evil, or Not Needed?</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:30 AM<br />
		Room: 404AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		A widely contested strategy in game production 
concerns the design document and to what extent 
it should rule the design process. Understood by 
all as an essential tool for effective planning, 
debate concerning ways to implement it differs 
greatly. This workshop will look at all sides of 
the argument and address how to create a game 
design document, how to follow it, under what 
conditions it should be deviated from, and how it 
best fits into the grand scheme of project 
planning.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="6"></a>W3 - Smart Games Break Out</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:30 AM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Out of the simulation genre has come a number of 
games designed to engage gamers in fixing, 
training, and learning. Smart Games today are the 
logical result of the transfer of ideas and 
technology that has toggled between the 
entertainment, military, and academic communities 
over the past 20 years. Walk away from this 
session with an understanding of how games are 
being used for training and education within the 
medical community, academia, and the mainstream 
consumer marketplace. See how Smart Games are 
becoming a growing niche, and learn how you can 
participate in its growth.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="7"></a>W4 - Working Smart: Understanding the Decision-Making Process at the Highest Levels</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 1:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
		Room: 411<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		How do major developers and publishers approach 
the game production process? What criteria 
determine whether a game gets green lighted or 
shot down when first pitched? How do they 
determine a game’s budget, the size of the 
development team, the production schedule, and 
best strategy to roll out the product in foreign 
markets? How do they deal with delays in 
production, changing consumers’ tastes, or 
unexpected glitches in the process? This panel 
will ask the industry’s biggest players to 
discuss how a game goes from idea to finished 
code. Be better at your business by hearing how 
the largest players in our industry approach the 
full spectrum of project approval and management.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="8"></a>W5 - Use the Web to Publish, Market, and Protect Your Game</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 1:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
		Room: 404AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		The number of online gamers is expected to 
continue to grow, just as the quality of web-
delivered games is expected to continue to 
improve. So what are the opportunities for the 
creative indie development house? And what are 
the new rules of development, distribution and 
delivery? Hear from experienced players in the 
demo/download, browser game, casual game, and 
secure networking space as they discuss 
successful digital delivery models in place today 
and how the sector will grow. Walk away knowing 
what content is selling, what the best 
technologies for the product are, how deals 
between independent studios and game aggregators 
are structured, and how the traditional 
publishing community is planning on moving into 
the sector.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="9"></a>W6 - Pitching Your Game Idea or Studio's Expertise: The New Rules</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 1:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		These days, you don't just pitch a full game idea 
to publishers. Often, you are pitching a subset 
of your studio's capabilities, or you may find 
yourself pitching to an investment firm or 
outside production company. This panel will 
discuss what studio managers must know about a 
modern pitch and what publishers and the 
financial experts are looking for from 
development teams. Panelists will discuss current 
trends in property development, new relationship 
strategies (work-for-hire, for example), and 
exactly what a publisher is looking for in a 
proposal document.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="10"></a>W7 - Persistent World Overview: Where the Bar is Now</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 3:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;5:30 PM<br />
		Room: 411<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Developers and publishers are diving into the PSW 
market at a rapid pace. So what are the main 
challenges facing the PSW development studio 
today? What are the costs of producing a MMOL 
title? What are the technical hurdles? How do you 
best prepare your live team? Our panel will 
discuss the content, tech, and pre- and post-
launch attributes that separate the good from the 
bad among persistent world titles. Learn what 
content is selling and where the market is taking 
massively-multiplayer gaming.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="11"></a>W8 - Funding Tip Sheet: Strategies for Tapping into Today's Money Stream</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 3:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;5:30 PM<br />
		Room: 404AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		The funding environment has changed significantly 
over the past year. And while new investment 
instruments are in play, securing pre-revenue as 
well as second-round funding hasn't gotten any 
easier. Our panel will discuss what specific 
funding models have traction among investors 
today, what publishers are funding, and how you 
can best package your business plan or game idea 
for maximum upside in the funding stage. Come 
away with an understanding of who is funding 
original concepts (even when publishers are not) 
and exactly what investors are looking for from a 
game company and game idea. Models to be 
discussed will include traditional advances 
against royalties, completion bonds, product-
specific private equity and traditional equity, 
and government funding.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="12"></a>W9 - Mobile Game Hit List: What Makes Them So Good</b><br />
		Tuesday, May 13, 2003, 3:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;5:30 PM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Take a mobile game on the cutting edge 
technically, one that is graphically beautiful, 
and has chalked up millions of downloads, and 
we'll show you a game that has something to 
teach.  This panel will be comprised of 
developers responsible for the world’s the most 
popular and creative mobile games. Listen in as 
they discuss their approach to design, 
programming, and business in the mobile sector 
and come away with a blueprint for better mobile 
game development.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
